This is precisely identical to: https://www.codewars.com/kata/52597aa56021e91c93000cb0

Regrettably, you did not compose that code. It was unmistakably written by an AI. Enlighten us as to why the input had to be stripped and why you opted for multiple discrete functions.

Input
* Line 2: Please change "numbers" to "integers".

Output
* Please format "Line 2" in <<bold>> instead of as a {{constant}}.

Constraints
* "[[num]]" is not defined in Input section or any other section in the statement.

* The ranges you state here are much wider than what is actually covered in the cases. Please reduce the ranges and/or revise the cases to cover the ranges better.

Cases
* Each pair of test and validator should be similar but different. Please revise the cases accordingly.

Thanks.
Thanks for the suggestions. I've applied them :)

Hello,
Thanks for the feedback.

This contribution was inspired by the Codewars problem you linked. I thought it would be a fun little clash as I had done it on Codewars before. If you think it's too "unoriginal," I can always add my twist to it.

As for the solution, I didn't write it using AI, as you claim I did. I'm a Java addict; I do all my work using Java, so I'm used to making functions for everything. If you go back to the previous versions of this contribution, you will see that the solution was written in Java. However, I changed it to Python because Java is pretty slow at running the test cases. If you want me to provide the solution in the same format as the code generated by the stub generator, I'm more than happy to do so.

I hope this cleared things up, and thanks again for the feedback ;)

Thanks for clarifying. I appreciate your response. If you're comfortable with Python and you've made the necessary adjustments to the solution, there's no need to provide it in the same format as the code generated by the stub generator. However, adding a little twist of your own to the code can make it more unique and showcase your creativity. It's always great to bring your own personal touch to the solutions. Keep up the good work!
